This paper explores the Egyptian hieroglyphic script as a computational system beyond conventional linguistic frameworks. Drawing on Goldwasser's analysis of conceptual categorization in hieroglyphics, we propose that the script functioned as an information processing architecture with multi-level encoding capabilities. We examine how this system was accessible across varying degrees of literacy and potentially shaped cognitive patterns throughout Egyptian society. The implications of viewing hieroglyphics as a computational rather than purely linguistic system are discussed in relation to Sapir-Whorf hypotheses and modern computational linguistics.
