\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:introduction}
Egyptian hieroglyphics represents one of humanity's most sophisticated early writing systems. Traditional analyses have approached it primarily as a linguistic tool, but recent scholarship suggests it may have functioned beyond the limitations of spoken language \citep{goldwasser2002prophets}. This paper proposes viewing hieroglyphics as a computational system—a structured approach to information processing that encoded, manipulated, and transmitted conceptual structures with capabilities exceeding contemporaneous spoken language.

