The existence of these reversed glyphs as formal elements in the script (rather than mere artistic variations) reinforces the hypothesis that hieroglyphic writing operated as a structured system for information processing with consistent logical operators and transformations—analogous to the logical operations in modern computation but expressed through visual rather than mathematical formalism.

